Nice one Arjuna.  There appear to be a flurry of articles this week on
zero-rating, mostly I suspect in reaction to Susan Crawford who had this to
say about zero-rating:  "Zero-rating is pernicious; it=E2=80=99s dangerous;=
 it=E2=80=99s
malignant."  More at
https://medium.com/backchannel/less-than-zero-199bcb05a868   I am much more
in sympathy with Kevin Werbach who says, =E2=80=9CI think #ZeroRating plans=
 should
be suspect but not preemptively banned. Some legit uses, but also
opportunities for mischief.=E2=80=9D

Other reactions:

Would a ban on zero rating throw the baby out with the bathwater?
http://www.techpolicydaily.com/internet/ban-zero-rating-risk-throwing-baby-=
bathwater/

Zero rating: Narrowing the digital divide in the mobile broadband market
http://www.techpolicydaily.com/internet/zero-rating-narrowing-digital-divid=
e-mobile-broadband-market/

and some commentary this week on the net neutrality debate in the US
specifically:

Shifting Politics of Net Neutrality Debate Ahead of F.C.C. Vote
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/20/technology/shifting-politics-of-net-neutr=
ality-debate-ahead-of-fcc-vote.html

Personally, what annoys me most is the sloganising of a complex debate.  If
only it were that simple.

Cheers... Steve

Thanks to Steve Song and Jon Crowcroft for their useful feedback.
