Hi all,

What all these satellite initiatives have to contend with the accelerating
spread of fibre infrastructure.  Not only is latency a non-issue with fibre
but it also has a much longer life-cycle than satellite technology.  The
steadily decreasing cost of fibre deployment combined with the growth of
low-cost wireless technologies to complete the last/first mile paints a
very appealing scenario.  Not to mention the fact that fibre can be
affordably integrated with other infrastructure deployment from roads to
water to waste further reducing costs.  Also, we have not yet fully plumbed
the depths of fibre capacity.  It's current capacity exceeds all current
demand and even then new discoveries like twisted fibre promise even more
capacity.

And then there is satellite technology.  High latency unless you have LEO
satellites which of course have much shorter lifespans.  There is a much
higher risk factor associated with satellite which is a combination of the
very high cost of launching satellites, the terrible cost of failure, and
the comparatively long lead time from technology conception to launch.  O3B
is a poster child for all of those issues.

SpaceX may be a different story.  If launching satellites is simply
piggy-backing on an existing space business, that may change things.

Cheers... Steve

